    <title>Combined summary - Adding New BIP Editors</title>
    <updated>2024-03-31T02:08:09.841676+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAMHHROw9mZJRnTbUo76PdqwJU==YJMvd9Qrst+nmyypaedYZgg@mail.gmail.com/T/#m77691bfa622dd48a0cf73e6745a59c766ed9afe5" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The governance and editorial process of Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs) has sparked significant discussion, emphasizing the need for a structured approach to enhance efficiency and inclusivity within the Bitcoin ecosystem. A key proposal includes separating repositories to mitigate conflicts and adhere to a "security through distrusting" philosophy, as exemplified by Joanna Rutkowska's insights at Black Hat Europe 2017 ([Joanna Rutkowska's presentation](https://www.qubes-os.org/news/2017/12/11/joanna-rutkowska-black-hat-europe-2017/)). This is suggested to maintain high-quality BIPs, advocating for editors proficient in multiple languages to improve redaction quality amidst challenges posed by non-native English contributors. The debate extends to whether the BIP process leans more towards administrative or editorial duties.

There's also consideration for refining the BIP numbering system, drawing inspiration from the IETF's RFC numbers management, to streamline deployment and reduce bureaucracy. Additionally, discussions touch upon the roles of Core maintainers and BIP editors, indicating potential benefits of independence to avoid centralization risks. The emphasis is on selecting BIP editors with diverse backgrounds to foster a comprehensive review process, highlighting the importance of technical expertise, open-mindedness, and unbiased perspectives in candidates.

The ongoing dialogue underscores the procedural responsibilities of BIP editors, focusing on assigning numbers and enhancing document quality without delving into the merit of proposals. The community seeks reasoned arguments and evidence-based reasoning for selecting new editors, aiming for transparency and informed decision-making. Proposals include delaying new editor appointments until after an upcoming CoreDev event, introducing administrative rights division, and considering geographic diversity among editors for improved responsiveness.

Notable endorsements for potential BIP editors like Kanzure and RubenSomsen emphasize their long-term involvement and balanced perspective. Proposed changes aim to shift editorial focus from technical evaluation to formal criteria adherence, involving the broader community in the technical review process. The governance of the BIPs repository faces scrutiny, with discussions on archival versus maintaining a unified repository for coherence despite potential conflicts of interest.

Finally, the trust placed in Luke Dashjr to select new BIP editors highlights the community's respect for his judgment, recognizing the urgency to address the bottleneck in managing BIP submissions. The anticipated inclusion of Kanzure and RubenSomsen aims to streamline the process, emphasizing efficient management, assignment of BIP numbers, and addressing amendments to enhance the Bitcoin development landscape.</summary>
